                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Choate</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">United States Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-08-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 27, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. Choate is informed by foreign office that the British reply to Li Hung
                    Chang’s request to name envoy to negotiate is similar to that <pb facs="0446"
                        n="348" xml:id="pg_348"/> made by the United States—that the views of Sir
                    Claude McDonald must be had before Li Hung Chang can be answered. The British
                    Government cares little who represents China if he is properly accredited; but
                    is not satisfied that Li Hung Chang is plenipotentiary or authorized by
                    competent authority to negotiate.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
